  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3025407214" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3025407214" />
    <a title="Xantha Page" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/64053858-xantha-page"><img alt="Xantha Page" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1498706322p2/64053858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3025407214?book_show_action=true">May 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Xantha Page" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Xantha Page" href="/user/show/64053858-xantha-page">Xantha Page</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780425086506" href="/book/show/1876848.Helliconia_Summer">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64053858-xantha-page?shelf=novels-and-novellas">novels-and-novellas</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64053858-xantha-page?shelf=scifi-etc">scifi-etc</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3025407214" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6108448694917138345">&quot;Science fiction on the grandest possible scale&quot; is about right. The political intrigue you find in these novels is about the standard for post-<i>Dune</i> SF, but Aldiss dispenses with the pulp conventions that particular series holds fast to—both stylistically, and in terms of the Hero&apos;s Journey stuff that <i>Dune</i> vacillates between criticizing and doubling down on. The sheer scale of the planetary invention is sometimes staggering. In each of the novels up till this point, Aldiss focuses on a particula</span>
  <span id="freeText6108448694917138345" style="display:none">"Science fiction on the grandest possible scale" is about right. The political intrigue you find in these novels is about the standard for post-<i>Dune</i> SF, but Aldiss dispenses with the pulp conventions that particular series holds fast to—both stylistically, and in terms of the Hero's Journey stuff that <i>Dune</i> vacillates between criticizing and doubling down on. The sheer scale of the planetary invention is sometimes staggering. In each of the novels up till this point, Aldiss focuses on a particular group of people—in <i>Spring</i> it's a few generations of people who occupy Embruddock/Oldorando, while here in <i>Summer</i> he narrows the scope chronologically but expands it geographically, tracing the movements of the many people involved in a particular bout of scheming and warring—but what really sets these novels apart is the slow, almost leisurely pace through which he wades through all this, enveloping the reader with details relating to religion, culture, technology, geography, ecology, linguistics, and almost any other field you could name. The best moments (and the moments that are most truly <i>SF</i>) are when he zooms out and gives the reader a bird's eye view of some massive geological or climatological shift and its ecological implications, or the entire social history of a particular custom, or the complicated life cycle of a particular organism—often interrupting a scene, conversation, or battle to do so, but always with a purpose. To tell you the truth I could have used more stuff like that. Looking over the reviews, it seems a lot of readers disagreed...<br /><br /><i>Dune</i> showed us what you can do when you not only have a lot of neat ideas but also care to integrate them closely enough to give the illusion of a living world, but if I'm being honest the world of Dune is pretty one-dimensional when you cut through the convoluted plotting. Its social history is essentially a binary opposition between hardship/virility and comfort/decadence, and its ecology is defined by the relationships between a few organisms (sandworms, humans, plants, and what else?). Maybe I've read too much Delany and <i>Viriconium</i> to really believe in thoroughly mapped-out secondary worlds, but for what it's worth, Helliconia is the most convincing such alien world I've spent time in.<br /><br />(Here's to hoping I can track down a matching mass market paperback copy of <i>Winter</i> to complete my set.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="6108448694917138345" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


