    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2783919816" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2783919816" />
    <a title="Jenai Goss" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17067392-jenai-goss"><img alt="Jenai Goss" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2783919816?book_show_action=true">Apr 12, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jenai Goss" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jenai Goss" href="/user/show/17067392-jenai-goss">Jenai Goss</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2783919816" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12210909948505854036">The second book in the Helliconia trilogy, it lives up to the amazing world-building of the first. Unfortunately, the non-linear fashion in which it is structured makes it far more confusing, and boring, than it should be. Every time tension builds there is no climax - instead we jump to the past, or future, or past within past, or a future flash-forward within a past flashback of another past flashback, etc. By the time we return to the initial high-stakes scene all the concern for the characte</span>
  <span id="freeText12210909948505854036" style="display:none">The second book in the Helliconia trilogy, it lives up to the amazing world-building of the first. Unfortunately, the non-linear fashion in which it is structured makes it far more confusing, and boring, than it should be. Every time tension builds there is no climax - instead we jump to the past, or future, or past within past, or a future flash-forward within a past flashback of another past flashback, etc. By the time we return to the initial high-stakes scene all the concern for the character or situation is gone.<br /><br />Fortunately the world - both the planet Heliconia with its very long summers and winters and the maneuvers of humans from the planet Earth, is quite interesting. Distorted legends of the past play out in the future in unexpected ways, and even death itself is different than it is on Earth.<br /><br />Unfortunately, the world cannot make up for the disjointed non-linear writing, or for the lack of characters we can truly follow. However, that itself makes it an interesting read - Helleconia is not a typical book where a person is the 'hero' and goes on a journey, rather it is a speculative science-fiction where the *world* is the hero itself, and we follow its journey around the sun.<br /><br />I actually stopped reading this some time ago near the end of the Summer book, as it was becoming too hard to read with its convoluted time jumps ruining whatever interest I had in the plot and characters. I love the *idea* of the long span of ages, unfortunately the impact was greatly lessened by going forward and back and in between so frequently. This was probably done to increase the mystery, such as the starting mystery of 'who is the dead body the queen sees, and how did he die?' But I think the book would have been far more effective had it simply gone through the long age from start to finish and not tried so hard to keep 'secrets' by saving the past for later flash backs.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12210909948505854036" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

