    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3820806972" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3820806972" />
    <a title="Chetan Tyagi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7146569-chetan-tyagi"><img alt="Chetan Tyagi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1421856720p2/7146569.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3820806972?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chetan Tyagi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chetan Tyagi" href="/user/show/7146569-chetan-tyagi">Chetan Tyagi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3820806972" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14883046922359898052">Helliconia Summer is the second book of the trilogy. While the first one was full of hope as the planet turned in favor of the main protagonists - the humans. However, Helliconia Summer is worse for humans as the future looks bleak with Winter approaching slowly but steadily. <br/><br/>In general, the central idea of the Helliconia series is captivating. A world where two scient races - Humans and Phagors - compete in the ever changing seasons and the advantage is continually swapped between the two sides</span>
  <span id="freeText14883046922359898052" style="display:none">Helliconia Summer is the second book of the trilogy. While the first one was full of hope as the planet turned in favor of the main protagonists - the humans. However, Helliconia Summer is worse for humans as the future looks bleak with Winter approaching slowly but steadily. <br /><br />In general, the central idea of the Helliconia series is captivating. A world where two scient races - Humans and Phagors - compete in the ever changing seasons and the advantage is continually swapped between the two sides. <br /><br />That said, sadly for me the books fail to do justice to this grand stage. If Aldis didn't keep reminding us that this was Helliconia by talking about Phagors, the storyline could easily fool you into thinking we were somewhere on earth in the middle ages. Characters are same (kings, queens, chancellors etc), culture is very similar and worse of all almost all words are the same as earth... how is it possible that a world light years away had the same language :-/ and the same human race. <br /><br />Also, the whole narrative is around a kings struggle with snippets of other countries and people. IMO, could have been a bit more diverse to showcase the planet. Also, the way Helliconia's history of how Freyr came, Phagors and humans evolved is succinctly told in the last 5 pages in a 400 page book was odd. Might have been much better if this would come out through the storyline gradually.. <br /><br />Overall, while the book is decent, it could have been a classic. Thus the disappointment.. A lowly 3 star for me. <br /><br />PS: if the third book in the trilogy ends up with a conclusion that Earth was actually the planet which was lost to the Helliconian planetary system (this event was briefly described in this book) it might be the ending that explains a lot of the above. We'll see.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14883046922359898052" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


